The model is built by 2 dense tanh layers of 512 and 256 units.
The optimizer is SGD with a learning rate (lr) =35e-5 and momentum (m) =0.99.
The low lr togheter with tanh stabilize the network during training while m helps learning faster.
Relu showed to be faster but nt as stable as tanh, with more units the model overfits and with less it seems to underfit.
RMSprop, adam, and MSE don't perform as well as SGD with the chosen hyperparameters. The model scores 83% on X_test and slightly overfits

The model has 1 more layer composed by 1024 units. The added capacity is compensated by regularizations.
Dropout is used gradually between all layers from a value of 0.1 to 0.3 to regularize more near the input.
L2 regularizer is also used with a value of 1e-4. Both Dropout and L2 helps the network to not overfit and remain stable.
BatchNormalization is not used because of its high instability. Adam replaces SGD because of better performances.
The model reaches 86% on X_test and doesn't overfit

Model_2_1 has a VGG-like structure with 3 blocks of 2 convolutional (CV) layers each and 3 Dense layers.
Both BatchNormalization (BN) and Dropout (DP) are used.
BN allows layers to learn from more stable distributions of inputs, thus reduces training time.
DP avoids units co-adaptation, its ratio increases gradually to regularize more near the input.
After every CV block, Maxpooling (MP) is used to reduce noise and filters are doubled to not lose information.
Padding="same" is also used. Images are small, thus reducing resolution further could be harmful.
The model's activation function is elu. I discarded tanh to avoid the "vanishing gradient problem".
I also discarded relu because "dying ReLU" was effecting the first layers of filters.
The model scores 95% on X_test and doesn't overfit

The generator applies rotation, width and height shift, zoom and 'nearest' fill_mode.
All the transformations’ values are 0.1, greater numbers are counterproductive.
This is due to the low resolutions of the images, even a little transformation can comprise essential features.
Because the numbers are usually in a solid color background, nearest filling seems the best option to cover empty spaces in transformed images.
The model generalizes better than 4_1, it never overfits and reaches 96% on X_test

Answer 3.1 (2p)¶

I computed the misclassification ratio for each class and investigated the class with the highest one (9).
Choosing the class with more misclassifications is unfair due to their unbalanced presence in X_test.
Overall, the model mispredict when images are blurry or the number is covered by obstacles like branches.
Even a human would find difficult to classify these samples correctly.
Furthermore, some images are labeled wrongly: the ground truth for X_test[7372] is 9 rather than 5

Answer 3.2 (4p)¶

In the first layer, some filters learned how to recognize horizontal, vertical or diagonal edges,
others seem to activate for bright or dark colors. The fifth from the bottom seems to recognize wave patterns.
Most second layer' filters separate the numbers in the image from the background.
In the third layer, most of the filters seem to consider more important the background and not activate on the number.
From the fourth layer on, the shapes are too abstract for a human to understand them

The model with conv_base fully frozen reaches a maximum of 50-60% accuracy. 
Fine-tuning the last block or the last 2 blocks let it converge at 90% on X_test but heavily overfits, reaching 99% on X_train.
This doesn't occur when fine-tuning the last 3 blocks, even tough accuracy remains the same on X_test.
All the training has been run with a low learning rate of 5e-6 to not impact greatly on the previous weights.
All models take advantage of vgg16 knowledge and converge in only 10-15 epochs
